SIMPLE: inebriate
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inebriate
<hw>In*e"bri*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Inebriated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Inebriating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>inebriatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>inebriare</ets>; pref.
<ets>in-</ets> in + <ets>ebriare</ets> to make drunk, fr.
<ets>ebrius</ets> drunk. See <er>Ebriety</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To make drunk; to intoxicate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The cups⟦br⟧
That cheer but not <qex>inebriate</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To disorder the senses of; to exhilarate or
elate as if by spirituous drink; to deprive of sense and judgment; also,
to stupefy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>inebriating</qex> effect of popular applause.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inebriate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Inebriate
<hw>In*e"bri*ate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To become drunk.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inebriate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Inebriate
<hw>In*e"bri*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>inebriatus</ets>, p. p.]</ety> <def>Intoxicated; drunk; habitually
given to drink; stupefied.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus spake Peter, as a man <qex>inebriate</qex> and made drunken
with the sweetness of this vision, not knowing what he said.</q>
<rj><qau>Udall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inebriate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Inebriate
<hw>In*e"bri*ate</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>One who is drunk or
intoxicated; esp., an habitual drunkard; <as>as, an asylum for
<ex>inebriates</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some <qex>inebriates</qex> have their paroxysms of inebriety.</q>
<rj><qau>E. Darwin.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>inebriated</ent>⟦br⟧
